<br>
The sky was deep. An empty void that extends far into the heavens. How lonely it must be for Luclin to hang without a sing star to keep it company tonight... The moon shines down on Miriam. It knew her pain. Night after night left alone, crying the same tears over and over. How many days had it been now? More like how many years... Miriiam hugs her knees to her chest. @#%$ them; @#%$ all of them to hell! Who needs them... who needs anyone! Her thoughts were pathetic coming from a girl dressed in full black leather, her face made up with makeup and nowhere to go. Alone she sits on a rock at a forests edge, over looking an empty and slowly dieing field. Everything took on a majestic glow under the dim moon, even Miriam. Why was she here? She really meant why was she still alive, but it was all the same in her mind. Her eyes are blood shot, her cheeks forever stained from salty tears that have slowly begun to stop. Where were they now? Her 'friends forever’? Now, when her heart aches and her soul screams for someone to care, there isn't a single person for miles who could hear... but that was her own fault, she wouldn't let them hear. Bastards, everyone single living-breathing person was a pain waiting to strike her fragile mind, her scarred spirit. What was left? Barely anything. What did she start with? Not enough... The days have been getting longer, and the nights lonelier, and everything harder to bare. <br>
<br>
&quot;Miriam?&quot;<br>
<br>
Her hands shake as she wipes the tears from her cheek and tries to hide any sign that she was crying.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yea, Del?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You ok?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll be fine, Delshad. Don't worry about it&quot;<br>
<br>
Delshad rubs Miriam's back and hugs her gently. &quot;Alright... Don't stay out here too long, its cold&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I won't&quot; Forcing a smile, she watches him leave. She wanted to cry out that everything wasn't all right, that nothing was, that she needed him here, needed anyone here. She wouldn't let herself trouble anyone else with her problems. Besides, Caelestis would be home soon. She could tell him everything, and if she couldn't, he would know anyways. Some how, Miriam knew Caelestis would never come home soon enough... Nothing could come soon enough with her hating herself the way she did. She hated that her hair color wasn't her own, that her eyes matched her fathers, that her clothes weren't how she wanted; that she acted like everything would be ok when she knew it wouldn't. The only thing that could come soon was her release, and even that wouldn't be as soon as she needed it... <br>
<br>
